\begin_layout Title
Direct exponential integration for linear SWE on sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Martin Schreiber
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
February 27, 2019
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There was a certain interest in using rational approximations for resembling
 exponential integrators with the SWE on the rotating sphere.
 Here, it was assumed that rational approximations must be used for solving
 the linearized SWE.
 This work investigates a way with the spherical harmonics transformations
 to directly exponentially integrate the linearized SWE without the Coriolis
 effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Linear operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the vorticity-divergence formulation, the linear operator is then
 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
\partial_{t}\Phi'\\
\partial_{t}\delta
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
 & c\overline{\Phi}\\
c\nabla^{2}
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
\Phi'\\
\delta
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Using spherical harmonics, the Laplace operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

 is also diagonal.
 Therefore, we can rearrange this system in 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 blocked matrices along the diagonal with each block relating to one particular
 associated Legendre polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset

 (ALP).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Exp.
 integrators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With exponential time integrators, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{t}=LU
\]

\end_inset

with
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
 & \overline{\Phi}\\
\nabla^{2}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and a direct solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U(t) & =\exp(tL)U(0).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For sake of convenience, we use the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $D=-\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G=-\overline{\Phi}$
\end_inset

, giving
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
 & G\\
D
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Eigen diagonalization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we can rewrite this to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix with all blocks independent to the other ones.
 From hereon, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 related to one particular ALP.
 Finally, we can work with an Eigen diagonalization of the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices, giving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(t)=Q\exp(t\Lambda)Q^{-1}U(0)=\exp(tL)U(0).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $LQ=Q\Lambda$
\end_inset

 an Eigenvalue decomposition with
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
see eigen_decomp.py
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{-G}{\sqrt{DG}} & \frac{G}{\sqrt{DG}}\\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\sqrt{DG}\\
 & \sqrt{DG}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and finally
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{-\sqrt{DG}}{2G} & \frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{\sqrt{DG}}{2G} & \frac{1}{2}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this, we can directly exponentially integrate the linearized SWE on
 the non-rotating sphere.
\end_layout

